Simple ways to help your child cope with his anger.
I often encounter parents who view the appearance of anger as something wrong and abnormal.
When a child expresses his anger openly - we don't know how to react, says psychologist Ekaterina Kess.
The expert encourages a brief discussion about these natural and human feelings - anger and resentment - that everyone experiences from time to time.
Aggression is physical action directed at another person, usually when we are angry.
When we adults are angry, when we're upset, we usually know what's happening to us and how to deal with it.
We can express, suppress, hide, hold on to anger, tell our friends or other relatives, jump on the couch in anger, smoke a cigarette (not the best way to vent our anger!), shower, throw a bullet at a table, and do other things we would not normally do.
We don't turn our aggression on others because we know all sorts of other ways to deal with those emotions.
Children who are angry do not understand what is happening to them, how to express it, or how to cope with it.
They may say, "Go away!" or "You're an idiot!" or "You're a bad mom", or "I don't see you", or "I'm not going to date you".
Children live in a literal sense, they're completely in the here and now, they're spontaneous and honest in their expression, and they're often trapped in a variety of emotions.
It is vital that parents do not prevent their children from expressing their feelings, including anger, or to shame or intimidate them.
