German researchers debate the number of victims of the Berlin Wall.
A new study suggests that the death toll at the former Communist-held border of East Germany may be much higher than previously thought, but doubts remain about the true number of victims.
According to data released Wednesday by the Checkpoint Charlie museum at the Berlin Wall, between 1945 and 1989, 1,841 people were executed by the communist authorities of the West Germany who tried to escape from their territory on the border with the Western Bloc zones and later West Germany.
The museum has been investigating border deaths for years and is adjusting the death toll every minute.
This year, 11 more deaths have been recorded, including a six-year-old boy who drowned while trying to reach his family in West Germany via what is now Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are deserters from the Soviet army.
"The ultimate extent of the damage caused by the double evils of communism and socialism is not yet fully documented", admits museum director Alexandra Hildebrante.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to escape the communist-controlled country are collected and preserved", Hildebrandt said in a statement.
But other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The number 1841 is not convincing", says Johannes Statz, an expert on the history of orientalism at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the S√ºddeutsche Zeitung.
He and other researchers at the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have only been able to confirm 260 cases.
Previously, researchers estimated that 138 people were slaughtered by the Communists at the Berlin Wall alone.
The State estimates that the number of victims may be in the thousands, including those who have died trying to escape by the Baltic Sea or reach the West through neighboring countries.
But it's still significantly less than 1841.
One of the reasons for the different number of victims could be different methodologies.
Checkpoint Charlie also lists all suicides of East German border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also lists deaths not directly related to violence.
"If elderly people in their 70s and 80s die of heart attacks after crossing the border", Hildebrante says, "it must be the result of this 'secret border.'"
However, the State believes that a distinction should be made between elderly people who may have died as a result of their experience of overtaking and those who died as a result of waiting for a long time in the hot weather on a bus at the border.
In addition, the counting of victims is not easy, since the Communist authorities in East Germany did not collect such statistics, and researchers have to search through various burned archives, the State says.
However, the State Group has recently produced new documents, and so it may soon be able to provide a new estimate of the number of victims.
