In Spain, the ability to form a government is threatened by the possibility of reducing the budget deficit.
On 12 July last, the European Commission (EC) concluded that Spain and Portugal had not implemented sufficient measures to bring the budget deficit levels down to the euro area's 3% of gross domestic product (GDP) target.
Despite the austerity measures implemented, the budget deficit in Portugal was estimated at 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year, compared with 5.1% in Spain.
The European Commission has, however, decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries while setting fiscal targets for the near term.
One of the reasons why the EC has not yet imposed sanctions on both countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many EU countries.
Further sanctions would only increase this negative sentiment.
Critics point out that the EC is inconsistent in its decisions, agreeing on uniform rules from the outset and then failing to apply them in practice.
For example, the president of the German Bundesbank, Jens Veidmann, has pointed out that Europe is thus losing confidence in itself by creating the impression that European Union rules are prescriptive rather than binding.
The Commission has now proposed and all Member States have agreed to extend the deadline for adjustment of the budget deficit to the end of this year for Portugal and to 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission vows to review progress in both countries in the coming months, while pointing out that both Spain and Portugal must be prepared to introduce further austerity measures if circumstances so require.
Initial forecasts suggest that Portugal's targets could be met within the timeframe and that the budget deficit could be reduced to 2,5% of GDP already this year.
This means that the national government has to implement austerity measures of 0,25% of GDP this year under the Stability Programme.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with an additional focus on controlling the cost of purchasing goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complex.
The budget deficit should be reduced to 4,6% of GDP this year, 3,1% next year and 2,2% in 2018.
In addition, consolidation measures should amount to 0,5% of GDP per year for the following two years.
The achievement of these objectives is made more difficult by the fact that the Spanish political parties have not been able to agree on a government for eight months and the growing possibility that Spain may have to hold its third early parliamentary election in a year.
However, opinion polls suggest that a third election would not significantly change the political landscape in the country.
The most popular party remains the People's Party led by current Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, which will again win less than 33% of the vote.
Only the Socialists have increased their popularity slightly, while the anti-austerity parties Podemos and Ciudadanos have declined slightly.
The People's Party wants the Socialists and Ciudadanos to join the government this month, otherwise it will not be able to adopt and submit the draft budget for 2017 to the European Commission for approval until mid-October.
As Rafael Hernando, a spokesman for the People's Party parliamentary group, has said, if a government fails to be formed and parliamentary elections are held for a third time, Spain will be the laughing stock of Europe.
