The State Energy Company "Latvenergo" is following the process of opening up the gas market from both the consumer and the potential seller's positions, said the company's press secretary Ivita Bidere.
'The decision whether to join the gas market as a trader in the future will be determined by the gas market model and legal framework.'
'We are therefore actively involved in the development and commentary of legislation and in making our own proposals,' said Bidere.
The BNS has already written that the Ministry of Economy (ME) in cooperation with the Public Service Regulatory Commission and the energy company Latvijas Gaze has developed a draft Cabinet Regulation on the 'Regulations on the trading and use of natural gas' which will change the principles of the operation of the existing natural gas market, ensuring that natural gas users have the right to choose freely their natural gas trader as of 3 April 2017.
In working towards a new regulation of the natural gas market, the EU aims to make the process of trading in natural gas as simple and user-friendly as possible.
The most efficient and user-friendly service solution is therefore the 'merchant-centric model', where all customer service activities are provided by the merchant - one contract, one invoice and one information and customer service point - leaving the technical aspects of the distribution system to the distribution system operator.
A similar solution is currently being implemented in the electricity market.
It is recalled that the market for households is to be opened gradually, and that after 3 April 2017 households that do not wish to switch to another natural gas trader will be able to continue to receive natural gas from the existing trader at a regulated price, thus becoming connected users.
'In this case, the obligation to supply gas to connected users at a regulated price is imposed on the public tenderer,' the ministry said.
Traders will have to choose a natural gas trader with whom to conclude a natural gas trading contract.
For the conclusion of an analogue contract, traders shall be provided with natural gas trading for a specified period of time by the existing natural gas trader at a price fixed by it.
The draft Cabinet Regulations detail the rights and obligations of the natural gas trader, system operator and user.
The rules shall lay down the arrangements for the supply and withdrawal of natural gas to users, the requirements for safe use of the natural gas system, the rights and obligations of the trader, public trader, system operator, user and owner of the gasified facility in relation to the supply and use of natural gas; the arrangements for the billing of services received, the amount of the delay rate, the arrangements for switching traders and for the supply of users in the event of disruption of the supply of natural gas; the arrangements for the supply of natural gas to connected users by the public trader.
