NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
According to NASA's latest climate models, Venus was once a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center have developed a model to study the history of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, which has a hot surface, no water, and an atmosphere made up almost entirely of carbon, once had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' slow rotation is due to its dense atmosphere.
But recent simulations suggest that Venus once had a flat, Earth-like atmosphere that was slowly rotating.
The model also looks at the earliest topography of Venus.
The planet was drier than Earth, but it had enough water and geographical diversity to support life and to keep water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the sun was 30 percent brighter.
In the GISS model simulation, the rotation model of Venus reveals that the daylight part of the day lasts for two months, explained GISS scientist Antonio Del Genio in a press release.
This process heats the planet's surface and causes matter to form thick clouds that act as a rain shield, shielding the planet from the sun's heat.
The result is a temperate climate, actually a few degrees warmer than the temperature on Earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, similar to the theory of evolution that scientists have hypothesized.
Although once habitable, Venus has been subjected to extreme heat and ultraviolet radiation for billions of years.
Their oceans were evaporated and their algae were scorched by ultraviolet rays.
When the water completely evaporated, all that was left was a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly greenhouse gas known today as Venus.
The scientists published the results of their new model of the climate of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
