Kepler measured the rotation of stars in the Pleiades.
The latest Kepler mission has helped astronomers to compile the most comprehensive catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in this star rotate at different speeds and how the rotation of stars can be related to the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other stars, we can learn more about the relationship between the mass, age, and even history of stars in their solar system", says Louise Rebula, a scientist at Caltech's Pasadena Infrared Process and Analysis Center.
The Pleiades star is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in this galaxy are just beginning to grow, reaching about 125 million years of age.
They're spinning at full speed.
At their maximum speed, these rising stars emit a large amount of stellar wind.
When winds enter the star's magnetic field, they slow down the star.
As stars age, their rotation slows.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by measuring the time between the appearance of a recognizable star region, such as the solar eclipse.
The latest catalogue of stellar rotation rates shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller ones.
Rebul compares stars to dancers, with larger-body dancers performing pirouettes more slowly than smaller-body dancers.
Rebul says that the Pleiades' "ballet" shows that slow-spinning objects are larger and more massive, while faster-spinning objects are very small stars.
Because of its close proximity, Pleiades serves as a vast space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars and their rotation rates.
Rebul says that the Pleiades helps to build theoretical models of star rotation in both directions for both older and younger stars.
We still have much to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down and stop completely.
Rebull and his colleagues have detailed their analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiadian stars in three new publications soon to be published in the Journal of Astronomy.
